d French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":37,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Burgate was born in 1345, in England, his father, Peter Burgate, was 31 and his mother, Amicia, was 20. He had at least 1 daughter with Eleanor Visdelou. He died in 1409, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1345–1409":"1345–1409","1355–1412":"1355–1412","1382–1436":"1382–1436","1315–1380":"1315–1380","1325–Female":"1325–Surnud","1315":"1315","1436":"1436","Abt 1382":"umbes 1382","1325":"1325","1412":"1412","1345":"1345","1355":"1355","1409":"1409","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Burgate, Suffolk, England":"Burgate, Suffolk, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1345–1409":"1345–1409","1355–1412":"1355–1412","1382–1436":"1382–1436","1315–1380":"1315–1380","1325–Female":"1325–Kuollut","1315":"1315","1436":"1436","Abt 1382":"noin 1382","1325":"1325","1412":"1412","1345":"1345","1355":"1355","1409":"1409","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Burgate, Suffolk, England":"Burgate, Suffolk, England","England":"England